xlQStyk2mBmWM4ea6S7Q=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing JSON interpolation limitations**\\n\\nI'm diving into the functionality of the public API, specifically regarding JSON string interpolation. I need to figure out a couple of things that might not be covered in the source material. For instance, what happens if I embed interpolation within a JSON string? I want to clarify how it handles large numeric literals and duplicate object keys, especially considering order preservation. There might be factors with whitespace handling and placeholder conflicts too that haven't been addressed yet.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring JSON number features**\\n\\nI’m thinking about the features related to JSON numbers and how they handle large integers or exponents. Instead of using Double, it might be better to use JsonNumber, which can accurately represent larger values, preventing precision loss. I wonder if it's worth testing to see how empty arrays and objects are handled since existing tests focus on non-empty cases. It seems important to provide support for empty structures, so I’m considering a feature that builds empty arrays and objects at any nesting level. However, I wonder if that might be too basic for the functionality we want.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Identifying functional features in JSON**\\n\\nI’m exploring another aspect of the object context, specifically considering the handling of null keys and string values. I noticed there isn't any testing for literal empty objects, which seems like an oversight. The existing functionality supports empty arrays and objects, which is good, but we need to highlight this as a new functional feature. I should add a test for “supportsEmptyArraysAndObjects” to ensure this aspect is covered. It could be a valuable addition to the current functionality.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Reviewing Scala public access**\\n\\nI'm considering how to test the JSON objects in my code. It seems like using `Json.arr()` and `Json.obj()` together is good, and I'm thinking that it shouldn't result in duplication. I also need to ensure that top-level test classes are public since Scala defaults to public, but the current class isn't explicitly set that way. Adding new methods seems acceptable without changing existing logic, and I’m confirming I don’t need imports. I'll use `edit append` before I wrap things up.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_3sCE5GtrU2e35na3kuPxFQr6|fc_04cd2cd8914dfbfc016a2aca5e9d0c81969e81226043fdf34f", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.circe/circe-literal_3/0.14.15/src/test/scala/io_circe/circe_literal_3/Circe_literal_3Test.scala", "edits": [{"oldText": "  @Test\n  def supportsTopLevelInterpolatedValues(): Unit = {\n    val text: String = \"top-level\"\n    val number: BigDecimal = BigDecimal(\"99.5\")\n    val jsonValue: Json = Json.obj(\"ok\" -> Json.True)\n\n    assertEquals(Json.fromString(text), json\"$text\")\n    assertEquals(Json.fromBigDecimal(number), json\"$number\")\n    assertEquals(jsonValue, json\"$jsonValue\")\n  }\n}\n", "newText": "  @Test\n  def supportsTopLevelInterpolatedValues(): Unit = {\n    val text: String = \"top-level\"\n    val number: BigDecimal = BigDecimal(\"99.5\")\n    val jsonValue: Json = Json.obj(\"ok\" -> Json.True)\n\n    assertEquals(Json.fromString(text), json\"$text\")\n    assertEquals(Json.fromBigDecimal(number), json\"$number\")\n    assertEquals(jsonValue, json\"$jsonValue\")\n  }\n\n  @Test\n  def supportsEmptyArraysAndObjectsInLiterals(): Unit = {\n    val document: Json = json\"\"\"\n      {\n        \"emptyArray\": [],\n        \"emptyObject\": {},\n        \"nested\": {\n          \"arrayWithEmptyValues\": [[], {}],\n          \"objectWithEmptyValues\": {\n            \"array\": [],\n            \"object\": {}\n          }\n        }\n      }\n    \"\"\"\n\n    val expected: Json = Json.obj(\n      \"emptyArray\" -> Json.arr(),\n      \"emptyObject\" -> Json.obj(),\n      \"nested\" -> Json.obj(\n        \"arrayWithEmptyValues\" -> Json.arr(Json.arr(), Json.obj()),\n        \"objectWithEmptyValues\" -> Json.obj(\n          \"array\" -> Json.arr(),\n          \"object\" -> Json.obj()\n        )\n      )\n    )\n\n    assertEquals(expected, document)\n    assertEquals(Json.arr(), json\"[]\")\n    assertEquals(Json.obj(), json\"{}\")\n  }\n}\n"}]}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2089, "output": 1143, "cacheRead": 29184, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 32416, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781189194081, "responseId": "resp_04cd2cd8914dfbfc016a2aca4a8fec8196b8aec7c1cfb9aef5"}}
